[SourceTitle "01 King's Gambit"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/120852"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 {The King's Gambit is a very feared weapon at lower levels of 
chess. It is a romantic opening that has been played for decades, and it 
deserves lots of respect. However, Black should not have much trouble equalizing 
against it with good play.} exf4 {I think it is best to simply grab the pawn 
because they are worried that going right into the main line is a risky choice. 
However, it is also the most testing choice and Black can equalize.} 3. Bc4 {Bc4 
is the main alternative to Nf3. It allows Qh4+, but it is best to simply develop 
with Nf6 or play super dynamically with d5.} Nf6 {Nf6 is a decent developing 
move. Black gets very good play.} 4. Nc3 c6 {c6 my look weird at first, but it 
is actually very logical. Black wants to play d5 next, freeing his position and 
kicking back White's light-squared bishop.} 5. d4 {d4 is the most direct 
approach. White seizes the center in an attempt to take advantage of Black's 
undeveloped pieces.} Bb4 {Bb4 prepares to castle, pins the knight, and threatens 
Nxe4.} 6. e5 Ne4 {Black takes advantage of the pin on the c3-knight.} 7. Kf1 
{Kf1 is a very cold-blooded move, simply stepping aside with the king. However, 
it is quite playable.} Nxc3 8. bxc3 d5 {Black does not even bother to drop back 
with the bishop and has a good position.} *

