1. e4 e5 2. f4 {The King's Gambit is a very feared weapon at lower levels of 
chess. It is a romantic opening that has been played for decades, and it 
deserves lots of respect. However, Black should not have much trouble equalizing 
against it with good play.} exf4 {I think it is best to simply grab the pawn 
because they are worried that going right into the main line is a risky choice. 
However, it is also the most testing choice and Black can equalize.} 3. Nf3 {Nf3 
is the main move, avoiding Qh4+ ideas.} g5 {g5 is the main line and the biggest 
test of the the king's gambit's validity. Black supports his pawn of f5.} 4. Bc4 
{Bc4 is the 'fast development' approach. White wants to create as many threats 
as possible quickly.} g4 {Black's pawn is not to be stopped.} 5. O-O 
{Sacrificing the piece.} gxf3 6. Qxf3 Qf6 {This is the main line of the Muzio 
Gambit. It is an effective weapon in blitz, but in a classical game White's 
practical compensation for the piece is not sufficient.} 7. e5 {Black sacrifices 
yet another pawn.} Qxe5 8. Bxf7+ {Bxf7+ is the unsound followup.} Kxf7 9. d4 Qf5 
{Objectively, Black is winning. However, White's compensation in a practical 
game should not be underestimated.} *

