[SourceTitle "02 Vienna Game and Bishop's Opening"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121130"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 {Nc3 is the defining move of the Vienna Game. Instead of 
immediately attacking the e5 pawn, White chooses to simply support his pawn on 
e4.} Nf6 {Simply developing the kingside knight is best.} 3. Bc4 {Bc4 is one of 
the many moves at White's disposal in this position.} Bc5 {White develops in the 
same way. We now have an Italian game with reversed colors where White is up a 
tempo.} 4. d3 c6 {c6 will support a later d5 break.} 5. Nf3 d6 {A solid move, 
defending e5.} 6. O-O Bb6 {Black will castle, play Re8 combined with Nbd7-f8-g6 
with good play.} *

