1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 {Nc3 is the defining move of the Vienna Game. Instead of 
immediately attacking the e5 pawn, White chooses to simply support his pawn on 
e4.} Nf6 {Simply developing the kingside knight is best.} 3. g3 {The fianchetto 
variation of the Vienna Game is a fairly decent choice.} d5 {If Black can play 
this d5 break, it is often a sign that he is equalizing.} 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 
Nxc3 {Forcing bxc3, which weakens White's pawn structure.} 6. bxc3 Nc6 {Black 
wants to tempt White into play Bxc6? which would tremendously weaken the light 
square around White's king after he castles.} 7. Ne2 {Ne2 is just another way in 
which White can choose to develop.} Be6 8. O-O Bd5 {Trading the light-squared 
bishops is very good for Black because it weakens the light squares on White's 
kingside.} 9. d3 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Qd5+ {It doesn't hurt to centralize the queen 
with check.} 11. f3 O-O-O {Black has a fine position.} *

