1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {Bc4 is the Bishop's Opening. It is very likely to transpose to 
another opening such as the Vienna Game, so there is not much that one has to 
know specifically for the early Bc4 move.} Nf6 {Black develops a piece and 
attacks White's pawn on e4.} 3. Nf3 {White sacrifices the pawn on e4.} Nxe4 4. 
Nc3 {White wants to stop Black from playing d5. For example, Nxe5 would have 
been answered with d5 with and edge for Black.} Nxc3 {Black begins to trade 
pieces.} 5. dxc3 {bxc3 would allow d5. dxc3 ensures that White's queen can also 
bear down on the d5 square.} f6 {f6 is a very solid move, supporting the e5 
pawn.} 6. Nh4 g6 {g6 stops Nf5 ideas.} 7. f4 Nc6 {The position is quite 
complicated, but about equal.} *

