1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 {Bc4 is the Bishop's Opening. It is very likely to transpose to 
another opening such as the Vienna Game, so there is not much that one has to 
know specifically for the early Bc4 move.} Nf6 {Black develops a piece and 
attacks White's pawn on e4.} 3. d4 {White tries to grab the center immediately 
with d4. This is a risky idea that can be effective against weaker opponents.} 
exd4 {Black takes on d4 knowing that e5 can be met by d5!} 4. Nf3 {White 
develops in order to regain the sacrificed pawn on the next move.} Bb4+ {This 
annoying little bishop check speeds up Black's kingside development.} 5. Bd2 $6 
{Bd2 is less accurate than c3.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nxe4 {Nxe4 is a very cold-blooded 
move, asking White to demonstrate his compensation.} 7. Qxd4 Nf6 {Black has a 
good position. The knight on f6 supports a d5 push if needed.} *

