[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 Four Knights Game"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121314"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {Nc3 signifies the 4 Knights Game.} Nf6 {Both sides 
have developed both of their knights symmetrically. This suggests that resulting 
play may be rater boring in nature but that is not necessarily the case. Now 
White has a lot of options. g3, Nxe5!, Bc4, and Bb5 are all common. d4 is known 
as the Four Knights Scotch, and that is covered in a different chapter.} 4. Bc4 
$6 {Bc4 is a common move among less experienced players. The reason it is not 
satisfactory is that it allows Nxe4.} Nxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 {Forking the knight and 
the bishop.} 6. Bd3 {White drops back with the bishop.} dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6 {Black 
develops and lends the pawn on e5 support.} 8. O-O O-O {Black is doing well.} *

