1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {Nc3 signifies the 4 Knights Game.} Nf6 {Both sides 
have developed both of their knights symmetrically. This suggests that resulting 
play may be rater boring in nature but that is not necessarily the case. Now 
White has a lot of options. g3, Nxe5!, Bc4, and Bb5 are all common. d4 is known 
as the Four Knights Scotch, and that is covered in a different chapter.} 4. Bb5 
Bc5 {Bc5 is not the most popular move by any stretch, but Black does 
surprisingly well after the Nxe4 tries.} 5. O-O {White delays taking on e5.} O-O 
6. Bxc6 {Bxc6 is a fairly harmless exchange line.} dxc6 7. Nxe5 $6 {The pawn 
should not be taken.} Re8 8. Nd3 Bg4 {Attacking the queen. Note that f3 is not 
possible due to the pin on the f2-pawn.} 9. Qe1 Bd4 {It is obvious that White 
has some problems.} *

