1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {Nc3 signifies the 4 Knights Game.} Nf6 {Both sides 
have developed both of their knights symmetrically. This suggests that resulting 
play may be rater boring in nature but that is not necessarily the case. Now 
White has a lot of options. g3, Nxe5!, Bc4, and Bb5 are all common. d4 is known 
as the Four Knights Scotch, and that is covered in a different chapter.} 4. Nxe5 
{T Nxe5 may come as a surprise for those of you who have never seen the 
Halloween Gambit before. White's idea is to sacrifice a piece in order to 
steamroll Black with pawns.} Nxe5 {Of course Black has to recapture.} 5. d4 Nc6 
{Nc6 is the most precise try. This is an important thing to remember because 
with correct play Black will be able to achieve a decent advantage.} 6. d5 Bb4 
{Black gives back the piece favorably.} 7. dxc6 {White should take, but now e4 
hangs.} Nxe4 {Qe2 does not lead to anything for White.} 8. Qd4 Qe7 {The Queen is 
dangerously lined up with White's king.} 9. Be3 {White blocks the e-file.} Nxc3 
10. bxc3 Bd6 {Black is a bit better due to his superior pawn structure.} *

