1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 {Nc3 signifies the 4 Knights Game.} Nf6 4. d4 {The 
Four Knights Scotch! White opens up the position with d4 just like he would in 
the Scotch Game, but he does so only after both sides have developed their 
knights.} exd4 {Black takes on d4 just like he would in the regular Scotch 
Game.} 5. Nd5 {Nd5 is a tricky move, but if Black is familiar with the line, he 
has nothing to worry about.} Be7 {Bc5 is also possible, but this Be7 move is 
very solid and offers Black good play.} 6. Nxd4 {Taking on d4 immediately is not 
very strong.} Nxd5 {The simplification process begins.} 7. exd5 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O 
{Black can play Bf6 next.} 9. Be2 Bf6 {Black will play d6 and develop his 
light-squared bishop. White has nothing.} *

