1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {d4 is known as the Scotch Game. It is one of the 
three most testing and popular ways to play against e5. White opens up the 
center immediately which means that Black no longer has to worry about 
supporting the e5 pawn. On the other hand, White has interesting dynamic play. 
Resulting play is usually rather sharp and interesting.} exd4 {Black should take 
the pawn. A passive move defending the e5 pawn would simply be bad.} 4. Bc4 {Bc4 
is known Scotch Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn in order to achieve fast 
development.} Bc5 {Black develops and protects his pawn on d4.} 5. O-O {O-O is 
more in the spirit of the Scotch Gambit, but White cannot hope for anything.} d6 
{Black prepares to develop his light-squared bishop.} 6. c3 {White wants to open 
up the position so that his development advantage will become relevant.} Bg4 
{Black indirectly defend his d5 pawn.} 7. Qb3 Bxf3 {Allowing Bxf7+!} 8. Bxf7+ 
Kf8 9. Bxg8 {Sooner or later White has to get rid of Black's knight, or else it 
will become a serious pest on White's weakened kingside after gxf3.} Rxg8 10. 
gxf3 g5 {Black has a fantastic position.} *

