[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121476"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {d4 is known as the Scotch Game. It is one of the 
three most testing and popular ways to play against e5. White opens up the 
center immediately which means that Black no longer has to worry about 
supporting the e5 pawn. On the other hand, White has interesting dynamic play. 
Resulting play is usually rather sharp and interesting.} exd4 {Black should take 
the pawn. A passive move defending the e5 pawn would simply be bad.} 4. Bc4 {Bc4 
is known Scotch Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn in order to achieve fast 
development.} Bc5 {Black develops and protects his pawn on d4.} 5. Ng5 {A less 
experienced player might try to take aim at the pawn on f7 by playing Ng5. 
However, this is completely harmless.} Nh6 {Black simply defends the f7 pawn 
with Nh6.} 6. Nxf7 {Everything else gives Black a free extra pawn.} Nxf7 7. 
Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6 {It appears that White will be able to recapture the 
bishop.} 9. Qxc5 d5 $1 {An important move to remember!} 10. Qxd5+ Qxd5 11. exd5 
Nb4 {Black has a much more pleasant position.} *

