1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {d4 is known as the Scotch Game. It is one of the 
three most testing and popular ways to play against e5. White opens up the 
center immediately which means that Black no longer has to worry about 
supporting the e5 pawn. On the other hand, White has interesting dynamic play. 
Resulting play is usually rather sharp and interesting.} exd4 {Black should take 
the pawn. A passive move defending the e5 pawn would simply be bad.} 4. Nxd4 
{White recaptures, the most natural move. This is the Scotch Game.} Nf6 {Nf6 is 
my move of choice and one of the most respected ways to handle the scotch game. 
Very fun, dynamic play will arise.} 5. Nxc6 bxc6 {Black has made a structural 
concession.} 6. e5 {White kicks Black's knight away.} Qe7 {White pins the e-pawn 
