1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Bc4 is known as the Italian Game. It is the second 
most popular choice behind the Ruy Lopez, and often leads to quiet positions 
where both sides are maneuvering their pieces.} Bc5 {Black develops his bishop 
to c5, avoiding all Ng5 ideas that arise after Nf6.} 4. b4 {The Evan's Gambit! 
White sacrifices a pawn in hopes of achieving some initiative that can be 
dangerous if Black is not prepared.} Bxb4 {It is best to just take the pawn, but 
Bb6 is also a perfectly playable.} 5. c3 {White attacks the bishop and prepares 
to push d4.} Ba5 {The bishop drops back.} 6. d4 {d4 immediately is the main 
choice, but one should also be aware of two other options: O-O and Qb3.} d6 
{Black supports the pawn on e5.} 7. dxe5 {dxe5 is possible, but not very 
dangerous.} dxe5 8. Qb3 Qf6 {followed by Nge7 and castles. Black is fine.} *

