1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Bc4 is known as the Italian Game. It is the second 
most popular choice behind the Ruy Lopez, and often leads to quiet positions 
where both sides are maneuvering their pieces.} Bc5 {Black develops his bishop 
to c5, avoiding all Ng5 ideas that arise after Nf6.} 4. c3 {White reserves the 
option to play d4 on the next move, instead of playing d3 next which leads to 
the Giuoco Piano.} Nf6 {Black develops and attacks the pawn on e4.} 5. d4 {d4 is 
a more aggressive line that is playable, but scores very well for Black.} exd4 
{Black has to take the pawn.} 6. e5 {e5 is an aggressive move that appears to 
force the knight to an awkward square. However, Black can play the thematic d5 
break.} d5 {Now the bishop has to move.} 7. Be2 {Be2 is the only alternative to 
Bb5.} Ne4 {Black centralizes his knight.} 8. cxd4 Bb6 {The bishop should simply 
drop back.} 9. Nc3 O-O {Black has natural play with ideas like Bg4. White is a 
tad better, but can definitely be outplayed from here.} *

