most popular choice behind the Ruy Lopez, and often leads to quiet positions 
where both sides are maneuvering their pieces.} Bc5 {Black develops his bishop 
to c5, avoiding all Ng5 ideas that arise after Nf6.} 4. c3 {White reserves the 
option to play d4 on the next move, instead of playing d3 next which leads to 
the Giuoco Piano.} Nf6 {Black develops and attacks the pawn on e4.} 5. d4 {d4 is 
