[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121520"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Bc4 is known as the Italian Game. It is the second 
most popular choice behind the Ruy Lopez, and often leads to quiet positions 
where both sides are maneuvering their pieces.} Bc5 {Black develops his bishop 
to c5, avoiding all Ng5 ideas that arise after Nf6.} 4. c3 {White reserves the 
option to play d4 on the next move, instead of playing d3 next which leads to 
the Giuoco Piano.} Nf6 {Black develops and attacks the pawn on e4.} 5. d4 {d4 is 
a more aggressive line that is playable, but scores very well for Black.} exd4 
{Black has to take the pawn.} 6. cxd4 {White will usually take back and force 
the bishop to move. However, White can also try e5 or O-O instead.} Bb4+ {Bb4+ 
is the only way to challenge White's center. Now White has a few ways in which 
he can block the check.} 7. Nc3 {Nc3 is an ultra sharp gambit line that is 
better for Black. Black only has to know one 20+ move variation to emerge on top 
after Nc3.} Nxe4 {Black grabs the pawn.} 8. O-O Bxc3 {Nxc3 is would be a big 
mistake.} 9. d5 Bf6 {The bishop drops back to safety.} 10. Re1 Ne7 11. Rxe4 
{White has one back a piece.} d6 12. Bg5 Bxg5 {The bishop trade is fine for 
Black.} 13. Nxg5 h6 {The knight is forced back.} 14. Qe2 {Qh4 can be met by the 
simple O-O.} hxg5 {Black has damaged his pawn structure somewhat.} 15. Re1 Be6 
16. dxe6 f6 {Black gives back a piece to close the e-file.} 17. Re3 c6 {Black 
looks to play d5 next.} 18. Rh3 Rxh3 19. gxh3 g6 {The king will be safe on g7 
and the knight can land on f5.} 20. Qf3 Qa5 {Black is doing great.} *

