1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Bc4 is known as the Italian Game. It is the second 
most popular choice behind the Ruy Lopez, and often leads to quiet positions 
where both sides are maneuvering their pieces.} Bc5 {Black develops his bishop 
to c5, avoiding all Ng5 ideas that arise after Nf6.} 4. d3 {d3 signals the 
Giuoco Piano, a very quite line. The resulting positions require a lot of 
maneuvering, and are hence difficult to turn into to theory and variations 
because both sides have so many possibilities.} Nf6 {Black develops his knight 
to the normal f6 square.} 5. Nc3 {Nc3 is a very classical way of playing, but it 
does not give Black many problems.} d6 {d6 is a solid move. The position is 
still symmetrical.} 6. Na4 {White goes for Black's bishop pair.} Bb6 7. Nxb6 
axb6 {Black has lost the bishop pair, but still has a solid position and easy 
development.} *

