1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez is the most testing way for White to 
play against 1. e4 e5. White immediately pressures the e5 pawn by attacking 
Black's knight on c6.} a6 {a6 is my move of choice, challenging the bishop on 
b5.} 4. Bxc6 {The Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation has never been considered to be a 
major test, but Black should certainly know how to handle it. Resulting play is 
very quiet and positional.} dxc6 {Black recaptures the bishop. Now if White 
plays Nxe5?, Qd4 is very good for Black.} 5. d4 {White can open up the center 
before castling, but this is completely harmless in my opinion.} exd4 6. Qxd4 
Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {The position has simplified to a queenless middlegame.} Bd7 {Black 
prepares a quick long castle.} 8. Be3 O-O-O 9. Nd2 Ne7 {Black develops as 
naturally as possible.} 10. O-O-O c5 {The bishop will find a home on c6.} *

[Event "1.e4 e5!: A Comprehensive Black Repertoire against 1.e4"]
[Site "Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation"]
