[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121819"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez is the most testing way for White to 
play against 1. e4 e5. White immediately pressures the e5 pawn by attacking 
Black's knight on c6.} a6 {a6 is my move of choice, challenging the bishop on 
b5.} 4. Bxc6 {The Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation has never been considered to be a 
major test, but Black should certainly know how to handle it. Resulting play is 
very quiet and positional.} dxc6 {Black recaptures the bishop. Now if White 
plays Nxe5?, Qd4 is very good for Black.} 5. O-O {White castles most of the 
time.} f6 {f6 is the most solid way of supporting the e5 pawn and also the main 
line.} 6. d4 {White opens the center. If White plays slowly instead, Black's 
bishop pair will easily come to life.} exd4 {Black takes on d4, opening the 
position.} 7. Nxd4 c5 {The knight is forced to retreat. The two possibilities 
are b3 and e2.} 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bg4 {Black develops with tempo on the rook.} 
10. f3 Be6 {Black has provoked f3. Now White has 3 different moves to choose 
from.} 11. Be3 {Be3 is a very logical move, hitting the c5-pawn.} b6 {Supporting 
c5.} 12. a4 Kf7 13. Bf4 Rc8 {Rc8 is the only decent way of defending the c7 
pawn.} 14. Nc3 c4 15. Nd4 Bc5 {Black develops as actively as possible and has a 
fine position.} *

