[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "10 Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121813"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez is the most testing way for White to 
play against 1. e4 e5. White immediately pressures the e5 pawn by attacking 
Black's knight on c6.} a6 {a6 is my move of choice, challenging the bishop on 
b5.} 4. Bxc6 {The Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation has never been considered to be a 
major test, but Black should certainly know how to handle it. Resulting play is 
very quiet and positional.} dxc6 {Black recaptures the bishop. Now if White 
plays Nxe5?, Qd4 is very good for Black.} 5. Nc3 {Nc3 is a possibility.} f6 
{Guarding the e5 pawn via f6 is the main line. Now White should try to open up 
the position with d4. Otherwise, he has nothing.} 6. d4 exd4 {Black of course 
has to take. White can take back with the queen or with the knight.} 7. Nxd4 
{Taking back with the knight does not evade the queen trade.} c5 {The knight is 
kicked back.} 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Be6 {Black develops naturally.} 10. Bf4 
O-O-O {Black castles long because the pawn on f6 makes short castling a bad 
idea.} 11. Ne3 Ne7 12. Rd1 Rxd1+ 13. Kxd1 {The position has simplified further.} 
g5 {The bishop is forced back to g3.} 14. Bg3 f5 {Black has equalized here. 
White can try either dxf5 or Be5 here.} 15. Be5 Rg8 {Black is doing fine.} *

