1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez is the most testing way for White to 
play against 1. e4 e5. White immediately pressures the e5 pawn by attacking 
Black's knight on c6.} a6 {a6 is my move of choice, challenging the bishop on 
b5.} 4. Ba4 {The bishop retreats. It is the most popular and ambitious move in 
the position.} Nf6 {Black brings his kingside knight into play and hits the e4 
pawn.} 5. O-O Be7 {Black prevents any potential play along the e-file, and 
thereby creates a real threat of Nxe4.} 6. Qe2 {Qe2 is known as the Worrall 
Attack. It is yet another way in which White can protect the e4 pawn.} b5 7. Bb3 
O-O {It is best if Black stays flexible.} 8. c3 d5 {d5 is a thematic move, 
freeing Black's position.} 9. d3 Re8 {White has at least 5 valid moves in this 
position, but Black has nothing to worry about. He can play Be6 later and just 
play the equal position from there.} *

