[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121834"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez is the most testing way for White to 
play against 1. e4 e5. White immediately pressures the e5 pawn by attacking 
Black's knight on c6.} a6 {a6 is my move of choice, challenging the bishop on 
b5.} 4. Ba4 {The bishop retreats. It is the most popular and ambitious move in 
the position.} Nf6 {Black brings his kingside knight into play and hits the e4 
pawn.} 5. O-O Be7 {Black prevents any potential play along the e-file, and 
thereby creates a real threat of Nxe4.} 6. Re1 {White supports the e-pawn with 
his rook.} b5 7. Bb3 d6 {d6 signifies the Closed Spanish. Black can also castle 
first and leave himself the option of playing the Marshall Attack.} 8. c3 {c3 is 
the main line. White prepares to grab the center with d4.} O-O 9. h3 {White 
prevents Bg4.} Nb8 {Nb8 is known as the Breyer Variation, and is one of the most 
interesting lines in the Closed Spanish. Black wants to reroute the knight to 
d7, where it is better placed to allow c5 than it is on c6.} 10. d4 {White's 
only critical move is to grab the center with d4.} Nbd7 {Black brings his knight 
to d7 as planned.} 11. Nbd2 Bb7 {Black continues to develop his pieces. Note 
that Black has placed all of his pieces on good squares.} 12. Bc2 Re8 {Black 
places his rook on the e-file and prepares Bf8.} 13. a4 {a4 is a sideline White 
can try in an attempt to undermine the b5 pawn.} Bf8 {The bishop drops back to 
f8, as planned.} 14. Bd3 c6 {Black is now ready to bring his queen to c7 for 
example.} 15. b3 g6 {With bg7 in mind.} 16. Bb2 Bg7 {Both sides have very 
playable, solid positions.} *

[Event "1.e4 e5!: A Comprehensive Black Repertoire against 1.e4"]
[Site "Ruy Lopez: Breyer Variation"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ruy Lopez: Breyer"]
[Black "Variation- Main Line"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "12 Ruy Lopez: Breyer Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "1e4-e5-a-comprehensive-black-repertoire-against-1e4/course/3767, variation/121836"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez is the most testing way for White to 
play against 1. e4 e5. White immediately pressures the e5 pawn by attacking 
Black's knight on c6.} a6 {a6 is my move of choice, challenging the bishop on 
b5.} 4. Ba4 {The bishop retreats. It is the most popular and ambitious move in 
the position.} Nf6 {Black brings his kingside knight into play and hits the e4 
pawn.} 5. O-O Be7 {Black prevents any potential play along the e-file, and 
thereby creates a real threat of Nxe4.} 6. Re1 {White supports the e-pawn with 
his rook.} b5 7. Bb3 d6 {d6 signifies the Closed Spanish. Black can also castle 
first and leave himself the option of playing the Marshall Attack.} 8. c3 {c3 is 
the main line. White prepares to grab the center with d4.} O-O 9. h3 {White 
prevents Bg4.} Nb8 {Nb8 is known as the Breyer Variation, and is one of the most 
interesting lines in the Closed Spanish. Black wants to reroute the knight to 
d7, where it is better placed to allow c5 than it is on c6.} 10. d4 {White's 
only critical move is to grab the center with d4.} Nbd7 {Black brings his knight 
to d7 as planned.} 11. Nbd2 Bb7 {Black continues to develop his pieces. Note 
that Black has placed all of his pieces on good squares.} 12. Bc2 Re8 {Black 
places his rook on the e-file and prepares Bf8.} 13. Nf1 {Nf1 is the main line. 
White wants to put his knight on g3 next.} Bf8 {Black will eventually tuck away 
the bishop on g7.} 14. Ng3 g6 {g6 has two functions. It takes away the f5 square 
from White's knight and prepares the logical Bg7.} 15. b3 {b3 is a possible 
sideline. Black wants to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, or even place it on 
a3.} Bg7 16. d5 {White closes the position.} Rc8 {Black prepares c6, attacking 
the d5 pawn.} 17. c4 c6 {Black wants to challenge White's central dominance.} 
18. Be3 Nb6 {Black continues to pressure White's center. Black has good play.} *

